</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>Endovascular therapy in pediatric stroke: utilization, patient characteristics, and outcomes</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Wilson%20JL"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Jenny L Wilson</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Jenny L Wilson</span>, <span class="degrees">MD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>a</sup>Division of Pediatric Neurology, Department of Pediatrics, Oregon Health &amp; Science University, 707 SW Gaines St MC CDRC-P, Portland, OR 97239, Phone: (503) 494-5856, Fax: (503) 494-6868</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Wilson%20JL"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Jenny L Wilson</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>a,</sup><sup>✉</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Eriksson%20CO"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Carl O Eriksson</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Carl O Eriksson</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MPH</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>b</sup>Division of Pediatric Critical Care, Department of Pediatrics, Oregon Health &amp; Science University, 707 SW Gaines St, CDRC-P, Portland, OR 97239</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Eriksson%20CO"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Carl O Eriksson</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>b</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Williams%20CN"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id3"><span class="name western">Cydni N Williams</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id3">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Cydni N Williams</span>, <span class="degrees">MD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>b</sup>Division of Pediatric Critical Care, Department of Pediatrics, Oregon Health &amp; Science University, 707 SW Gaines St, CDRC-P, Portland, OR 97239</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Williams%20CN"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Cydni N Williams</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>b</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>a</sup>Division of Pediatric Neurology, Department of Pediatrics, Oregon Health &amp; Science University, 707 SW Gaines St MC CDRC-P, Portland, OR 97239, Phone: (503) 494-5856, Fax: (503) 494-6868</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>b</sup>Division of Pediatric Critical Care, Department of Pediatrics, Oregon Health &amp; Science University, 707 SW Gaines St, CDRC-P, Portland, OR 97239</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="_fncrsp93pmc__">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline">Corresponding author.</p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Issue date 2017 Apr.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC6394403  NIHMSID: NIHMS1009375  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28233666/" class="usa-link">28233666</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pediatrneurol.2017.01.013" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Pediatr Neurol</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="S1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Background and Purpose</h3>
<p id="P1">Despite strong evidence for endovascular therapy in adults with acute arterial ischemic stroke, limited data exists in children. We aimed to describe endovascular therapy utilization and explore outcomes in a national sample of pediatric arterial ischemic stroke.</p></section><section id="S2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods</h3>
<p id="P2">We queried the 2012 Kids’ Inpatient Database for children aged &gt;28 days to 20 years with ICD-9-CM codes for arterial ischemic stroke and evaluated groups based on procedure code for endovascular therapy. Poor outcome was defined as need for tracheostomy or gastrostomy, discharge to rehabilitation facility, or death. Logistic regression evaluated the association between endovascular therapy and poor outcome, adjusted for age, disease severity (hemiplegia, critical care interventions, neurosurgical interventions), and comorbidities.</p></section><section id="S3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h3>
<p id="P3">We identified 3184 pediatric discharges with a diagnosis code for arterial ischemic stroke. Thirty-eight (1%) had an endovascular therapy procedure code. Endovascular therapy patients were older (10.2 versus 4.5 years, p&lt;.001), and more likely to have hemiplegia/paresis (RR 3.8, 95% CI 2.0–7.4), aphasia (RR 5.3, 95% CI 2.8–10.1), and facial droop (RR 4.0, 95% CI 1.9–8.7). Endovascular therapy was not associated with critical care and neurosurgical interventions or intracranial hemorrhage. Length of hospitalization, mortality, and discharge disposition were similar between groups. In a multivariable model, endovascular therapy was not associated with poor outcome (aOR 1.7, 95% CI 0.7–4.1).</p></section><section id="S4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusions</h3>
<p id="P4">In a national sample of children with a diagnosis of arterial ischemic stroke, endovascular therapy was infrequently utilized. Patients with a procedure code for endovascular therapy had significant stroke-related deficits, but outcomes were similar to children who did not receive endovascular therapy. Our data in conjunction with evidence of benefit in adults support consideration of endovascular therapy for select children with acute stroke.</p></section><section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> pediatric stroke, endovascular treatment, ischemic stroke, thrombectomy, outcomes research</p></section></section><hr class="headless">
<p id="P5">Arterial ischemic stroke (AIS) occurs in 1–8/100,000 children per year,<sup><a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>–<a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a></sup> leaving 60% with permanent neurologic deficits.<sup><a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>, <a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a></sup> The diagnosis of AIS is often delayed in children who are more likely to have a stroke mimic.<sup><a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a></sup> This delay makes it more difficult to offer acute therapies to children and to study in controlled trials.</p>
<p id="P6">In adults, acute therapies including intravenous tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) and endovascular therapy are established as beneficial. Endovascular therapies are catheter-based interventions to recanalize the vessel, including intra-arterial thrombolysis and mechanical techniques such as stent retrieval.<sup><a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a></sup> The 2015 AHA guidelines which recommend endovascular therapy for adults presenting within 6 hours with large vessel occlusion, also state that use of endovascular therapy with stent retrievers may be reasonable in children &lt; 18 years.<sup><a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a></sup></p>
<p id="P7">No clinical trials have evaluated outcomes of pediatric endovascular therapy, with evidence coming from case reports and single center series.<sup><a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a>–<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a></sup> We aimed to report the utilization of endovascular therapy in pediatric AIS, identify characteristics associated with receipt of endovascular therapy, and explore associated outcomes among a nationally representative sample of children with AIS in the United States (US).</p>
<section id="S5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods</h2>
<p id="P8">We performed a retrospective cohort analysis of administrative data within the 2012 Kids Inpatient Database (KID) from the Agency of Healthcare Research and Quality<sup><a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a></sup> to evaluate the utilization of endovascular therapy in pediatric AIS and to explore characteristics and outcomes associated with endovascular therapy. The 2012 KID contains pediatric discharges from 44 states and 4,179 hospitals for children ages 20 years and younger in the US. The large sample size and stratified probability sampling design allows for national estimates using weighting procedures. The KID includes demographic information, payer, hospital characteristics, ICD-9-CM diagnosis codes, ICD-9-CM procedure codes, clinical classification software (CCS) codes that group ICD-9-CM diagnosis and procedure codes, length of stay, hospital charges, admission and discharge status, and in-hospital death. The data are anonymous. Use of the KID is considered non-human subjects research and is exempt from Oregon Health and Science University’s institutional review board evaluation.</p>
<p id="P9">We identified AIS patients aged &gt;28 days to 20 years with ICD-9-CM diagnosis codes for pre-cerebral (433; includes basilar, vertebral, carotid) and cerebral arterial occlusions or narrowing (434). We limited our AIS cohort to codes 433 and 434, which have the best reported true positive rates for diagnosis codes among inpatients with arterial ischemic strokes.<sup><a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a>–<a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">18</a></sup> The endovascular therapy group was identified by an ICD-9-CM procedure code for endovascular thrombectomy or embolectomy (39.74). Demographic and clinical characteristics were evaluated by groups of endovascular therapy versus other therapy (patients without an endovascular therapy procedure code). ICD-9-CM diagnosis, ICD-9-CM procedure, and CCS codes were used to define other variables and compare by groups (please see <a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">online supplement</a>). We also created comorbidity categories for analysis from variable coding outlined in the <a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">online supplement</a>. Critical care interventions were defined as mechanical ventilation, non-invasive ventilation, intracranial pressure monitor, arterial catheterization, or central venous catheterization. Neurosurgical interventions were defined as decompressive craniectomy, intracranial hematoma drainage, ventriculoperitoneal shunt, or externalized ventricular drain. We created a composite variable to define poor outcome as need for tracheostomy or gastrostomy during hospitalization, in-hospital mortality, or discharge to a nursing or rehabilitation facility.</p>
<p id="P10">Analyses were conducted in SPSS for Windows (Version 23, IBM Corporation) with the complex samples add-on. National weighted estimates and their standard errors were calculated. The finite population correction was used to adjust standard errors because results were not generalized beyond 2012 and because the KID contains a large percentage of children treated in US hospitals. All weighted estimates were rounded to the nearest whole number. Per the KID data use agreement, estimates with totals &gt; 0 and ≤10 are not reported in results. Calculation of population incidence was performed using US census data.<sup><a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a></sup> Categorical variable estimates were rounded to whole numbers and percentages. Continuous variable estimates were expressed as means with standard error. Bivariate analyses used Chi-Square tests with Fisher Exact correction for categorical variables and t-tests for continuous variables. Bivariate results were reported with p-values and Relative Risk (RR) with 95% Confidence Interval (CI) for categorical variables. A p-value of &lt;.05 defined statistical significance. A logistic regression model for “poor outcome” was created to evaluate the association between endovascular therapy and poor outcome adjusted for patient age, disease severity (hemiplegia, critical care interventions, neurosurgical interventions), and comorbidity categories. Multivariable model results were reported as adjusted Odds Ratio (aOR) and 95% CI.</p></section><section id="S6"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h2>
<p id="P11">AIS codes were identified in 3184 pediatric discharges, corresponding to an incidence of 3.7 cases/100,000 US children in 2012. Endovascular therapy procedure codes were identified in 38 (1%) patients. <a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a> presents demographic and admission characteristics by endovascular therapy group. Endovascular therapy patients ranged from 2–20 years, with 78% ≥ 11 years, and endovascular therapy patients were significantly older (10.2 versus 4.5 years, p &lt;.001). Overall, 47% of AIS patients were female and endovascular therapy did not vary with sex. Government sponsored insurance (Medicaid) was less common in the endovascular therapy group (RR 0.2, 95% CI 0.1–0.6). However, endovascular therapy was more common in public versus privately owned hospitals (RR 3.1, 95% CI 1.6–6.1). Children with AIS were infrequently treated at freestanding children’s hospitals, and receipt of endovascular therapy did not differ by type of hospital (p=.17).</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T1"><h3 class="obj_head">Table 1.</h3>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P27">Demographic and Admission Characteristics by Receipt of Endovascular Therapy</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
