<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p">
<div class="fn" id="TFN1"><p id="P28">Per the Kids’ Inpatient Database data use agreement, weighted estimates with values ≤ 10 cases are not reported. All reported values are weighted estimates rounded to the nearest whole number or percentage and may not sum to totals.</p></div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN2"><p id="P29">Abbreviations: SEM-standard error of mean</p></div>
</div></section><p id="P12">Clinical characteristics by endovascular therapy group are presented in <a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>. Overall, 13% of children with AIS had carotid vessel occlusion codes. Codes for basilar or vertebral occlusions were seen in 4% of all AIS patients with a non-significant trend toward higher rates in the endovascular therapy group (RR 3.0, 95% CI 1.0–8.3). Overall, 71% had at least one comorbid condition identified as an AIS risk factor. Cardiac comorbidities were most common in both groups (42% endovascular therapy versus 28% other, p=.07). Congenital heart disease accounted for the majority of the difference between the groups in the cardiac category. Other comorbid categories were similar including arteriopathy, systemic disorders, head and neck disorders, and hypercoagulable states. The frequency of sickle cell disease was not different between groups, though the numbers in the endovascular therapy group were very small. Endovascular therapy patients were more likely to have significant stroke-related symptoms during their hospitalization, including hemiplegia or paresis (RR 3.8, 95% CI 2.0–7.4), aphasia (RR 5.3, 95% CI 2.8–10.1), and facial droop (RR 4.0, 95% CI 1.9–8.7). Seizure was significantly less common in the endovascular therapy group (RR 0.2, 95% CI 0.1–0.7); seizure incidence decreased significantly with increasing age (p&lt;.001).</p>
