<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="TFN3"><p id="P31">Per the Kids’ Inpatient Database data use agreement, weighted estimates with values ≤ 10 cases are not reported. All reported values are weighted estimates rounded to the nearest whole number or percentage and may not sum to totals.</p></div></div></section><p id="P13"><a href="#T3" class="usa-link">Table 3</a> presents hospital procedures and therapies by endovascular therapy group. Critical care interventions were common, occurring in 43% of children with AIS, and did not differ by endovascular therapy group. No patients in the endovascular therapy group received blood product transfusions, while 17% in the standard therapy group received packed red cell transfusions during admission (p=.002). Of the 520 patients who received transfusions, 17% had sickle cell disease. TPA administration was uncommon overall (2%), but was significantly more common in the endovascular therapy group (RR 33.6, 95% CI 18.4–61.3). TPA administration increased with increasing patient age (p=.01). Neurosurgical interventions were uncommon, occurring in 3–4% of patients in both groups (p&gt;.99).</p>
