</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p">
<div class="fn" id="TFN4"><p id="P33">Per the Kids’ Inpatient Database data use agreement, weighted estimates with values ≤ 10 cases are not reported. All reported values are weighted estimates rounded to the nearest whole number or percentage and may not sum to totals.</p></div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN5"><p id="P34">Abbreviations: SEM-standard error of mean</p></div>
</div></section><p id="P14">Outcomes were similar in both groups (<a href="#T3" class="usa-link">Table 3</a>). Intracranial hemorrhage occurred in 8% of all children with AIS, and did not differ by endovascular therapy group (p=.12). Intracranial hemorrhage varied with tPA (22% among patients with endovascular therapy and tPA, 10% among tPA only patients, 7% among endovascular therapy only patients, 8% among patients with neither tPA nor endovascular therapy codes). However, patient numbers were low and intracranial hemorrhage was not significantly associated with endovascular therapy and tPA combination compared to other groups (p=.06) or with tPA overall (p=.16). In-hospital mortality was 10% and did not differ by endovascular therapy group. Lengths of stay and hospital charges were also similar. Poor outcome, defined as need for tracheostomy, gastrostomy, discharge to rehabilitation facility, or death, did not differ by group (45% endovascular therapy versus 30% other, p=.07). In a multivariable model of poor outcome adjusted for patient age, disease severity (hemiplegia, critical care intervention, neurosurgical intervention), and comorbidity categories, endovascular therapy was not associated with poor outcome (aOR 1.7, 95% CI 0.7–4.1).</p></section><section id="S7"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Discussion</h2>
<p id="P15">Among a national sample of &gt;3,000 pediatric discharges with AIS codes, 1% had procedures codes for endovascular therapy, encompassing the largest cohort of pediatric endovascular therapy reported to date. Children in the endovascular therapy group were older, often had cardiac comorbidities, and were more likely to have substantial neurologic deficits. Adding to the limited safety data for pediatric endovascular therapy, rates of significant complications, such as intracranial hemorrhage and need for critical care or neurosurgical procedures, did not differ with endovascular therapy. Our data showed no difference in hospital mortality or poor outcome with endovascular therapy.</p>
<p id="P16">We found a pediatric AIS incidence of 3.7/100,000 US children in 2012. Studies of ischemic stroke in children report incidences ranging from 0.6–7.9/100,000 children per year.<sup><a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">2</a>, <a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>, <a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a>, <a href="#R19" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R19">19</a>–<a href="#R26" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R26">26</a></sup> Our incidence is consistent with recent studies using similar populations and methods.<sup><a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">22</a>, <a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a></sup> We found endovascular therapy codes in 1% of our AIS cohort. This is consistent with early utilization rates in adults with ischemic stroke (0.6% in 2009)<sup><a href="#R27" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R27">27</a></sup> and with estimates from single center reports performing about 0.5 endovascular therapy cases per year in children.<sup><a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>, <a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a></sup> In 2012, endovascular therapy was not a universally accepted therapy in adults, potentially limiting pediatric utilization.<sup><a href="#R28" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R28">28</a></sup> Diagnostic delay reported in pediatric stroke may limit utilization of acute therapies like endovascular therapy.<sup><a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a>, <a href="#R29" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R29">29</a></sup> Institutional and technical factors may preclude endovascular therapy in younger patients, including limited access to facilities or providers capable of performing endovascular therapy in children, and lack of pediatric-specific devices.</p>
<p id="P17">TPA was given to 2% of patients overall, comparable to other reports.<sup><a href="#R30" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R30">30</a></sup> TPA was more common in the endovascular therapy group, which is not surprising given the overlap in eligibility for these therapies. There may also be a center or provider bias toward more intervention. Additionally, this dataset does not distinguish intravenous tPA from intra-arterial tPA, so the overlap may be explained by patients who received intra-arterial tPA in the context of their endovascular procedure.</p>
<p id="P18">Children with substantial deficits like hemiparesis were significantly more common in the endovascular therapy group, which may reflect large vessel occlusion or earlier recognition of stroke. Medicaid insurance was less common in the endovascular therapy group. Children with Medicaid have been shown to have worse outcomes in a number of disease states.<sup><a href="#R31" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R31">31</a>–<a href="#R33" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R33">33</a></sup> Among adult stroke patients, African-Americans, the uninsured, and Medicare patients have been shown to be less likely to receive endovascular therapy.<sup><a href="#R34" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R34">34</a></sup> The impact of insurance status, socioeconomic status, and race on pediatric stroke interventions, access to care, and outcomes is an area that warrants further study.</p>
<p id="P19">Seizure was less common in the endovascular therapy group, which may be explained by the higher rates of seizures in younger children in this cohort, consistent with other reports in pediatric stroke.<sup><a href="#R35" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R35">35</a></sup> Seizure presentation has not been associated with delay in pediatric stroke diagnosis.<sup><a href="#R29" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R29">29</a>, <a href="#R36" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R36">36</a></sup> Nonetheless, it is possible that children presenting with seizure and motor deficits are initially presumed to have a Todd’s paralysis, precluding a diagnosis within a window for acute intervention. Alternatively, patients with seizure at presentation may have been miscoded as having a stroke. Notably, 42% of patients in the endovascular therapy group had a cardiac comorbidity, portending high risk for embolism and large vessel occlusion. This is consistent with a review of case reports, in which 34.5% of children receiving endovascular therapy had cardiac pathology.<sup><a href="#R37" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R37">37</a></sup> Stroke programs planning for pediatric endovascular therapy need to consider the factors unique to cardiac patients such as vascular anatomic differences and higher likelihood of being hospitalized at the time of stroke onset.</p>
<p id="P20">Endovascular therapy is established as beneficial in adult stroke, though data is limited in children. In adults, five trials between 2010 and 2015 demonstrated efficacy of endovascular therapy using stent retrievers in anterior circulation stroke.<sup><a href="#R38" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R38">38</a>–<a href="#R42" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R42">42</a></sup> These trials showed significant improvements in the Modified Rankin Scale (MRS). Efficacy of endovascular therapy in children is not known, though a recent review of the 29 published cases of mechanical thrombectomy using modern devices in children was encouraging, with no deaths and 86.7% having a good outcome defined as MRS ≤ 2.<sup><a href="#R37" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R37">37</a></sup> A historical comparison group of children with large vessel occlusion not receiving endovascular therapy has not been reported, making it difficult to draw definitive conclusions about the efficacy of endovascular therapy in children from case reports.</p>
<p id="P21">Outcomes in our study were not associated with endovascular therapy. Though disability measures are not available through KID, our data on mortality and complications are likely to be more representative of the population of children undergoing endovascular therapy versus case reports and series when considering publication bias. Our study found 45% of the endovascular therapy group had a poor outcome and mortality was 10%, though this did not differ from the group without endovascular therapy codes. In a subgroup analysis of patients with codes for pre-cerebral occlusion and hemiparesis, we found no differences in outcomes with endovascular therapy procedure code, though numbers were small. It was encouraging that even though the endovascular therapy patients had more frequent severe deficits such as hemiparesis during hospitalization, they did not differ in outcome measurements from other AIS patients in our cohort.</p>
<p id="P22">Patients in the endovascular therapy group without procedure codes for tPA were at no higher risk of hemorrhage than other AIS patients, though patients with the combination of codes for endovascular therapy and tPA trended toward higher rates of hemorrhage. In the few reported cases of combined intravenous tPA and endovascular therapy in children, hemorrhage was not reported.<sup><a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>, <a href="#R43" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R43">43</a>, <a href="#R44" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R44">44</a></sup> A review of 34 patients treated with endovascular therapy reported hemorrhage in 23.5%, all of whom were treated with intra-arterial TPA.<sup><a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">10</a></sup> Data from adult stroke trials supports about a three-fold higher hemorrhage rate with intra-arterial thrombolysis, with rates around 10%.<sup><a href="#R45" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R45">45</a></sup> We suspect the trend toward higher rates of hemorrhage seen in the group with procedure codes for both tPA and endovascular therapy may be due to the use of intra-arterial tPA, though rates were still higher than those reported in adults, warranting further evaluation of the use of tPA and endovascular therapy in combination among pediatric patients.</p>
<p id="P23">This study is based on administrative data which allows for evaluation of a large sample of hospitalized children, which is useful for exploring outcomes after an infrequently performed procedure, though the small number of patients with endovascular therapy codes may have limited some analyses. However, the use of administrative data comes with the limitation that AIS and endovascular therapy patients are included based on diagnostic and procedure codes, and could not be confirmed with chart review. The sensitivity and specificity of ICD-9 codes for stroke vary based on population studied, with a positive predictive value of 77–84% in pediatric studies.<sup><a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a>, <a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">17</a></sup> The limited sensitivity and specificity of the ICD-9-CM stroke codes means our overall cohort of AIS patients likely includes some patients without AIS and does not capture some patients with AIS. The large sample size and high sampling frequency of pediatric discharges within KID yield a nationally representative sample that helps mitigate this limitation and KID studies have produced similar incidences to other research methods in a variety of pediatric diseases.<sup><a href="#R46" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R46">46</a>–<a href="#R48" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R48">48</a></sup> Additionally, KID does not include information on devices or techniques used, which have evolved since 2012. Details of clinical symptoms at presentation, National Institutes of Health Stroke Scale Score, time to therapy, repeated admissions, laboratory data, residual discharge deficits, and outcome past discharge are not available in this dataset.</p></section><section id="S8"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Summary</h2>
<p id="P24">Among a national cohort of children with a diagnosis code for AIS, 1% had a procedure code for endovascular therapy. Patients in the endovascular therapy group were older and had substantial neurologic deficits. Outcomes and complications including death, neurosurgical procedure, hemorrhage, discharge status, and length of hospitalization were not different among patients in the endovascular therapy group, adding to the limited safety data for pediatric endovascular therapy. While endovascular therapy merits consideration in children with acute stroke, further research is needed to understand if this therapy improves outcomes in this population.</p></section><section id="SM1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Supplementary Material</h2>
